<LG>
<L>Unlike her &s;elf, a Si&s;ter <HI>Merah</HI> had</L>
<L>(The Joy and Grief of many a Noble Lad)</L>
<L>Fair MICHAL &s;he was call'd, who&s;e lovely F$</L>
<L>No <HI>Feature</HI> wanted that could add a Grace.</L>
<L>Her <HI>Body</HI> delicate. Wherein en&s;hrin'd,</L>
<L>As in its Temple, dwelt a <HI>virtuous Mind</HI>.</L>
<L>Engaging <HI>Sweetne&s;s</HI> beamed from her Eye:</L>
<L>And on her <HI>Choo$</HI> &s;ate Maiden-Mode&s;ty.</L>
<L>Her <HI>courteous Mein</HI> gave Proof to all, that &s;he</L>
<L>From <HI>Pride</HI>, and <HI>Haughtine&s;s</HI> of Mind was <HI>free</HI>.</L>
<L>For of the <HI>Meane&s;t</HI> &s;he would notice take.</L>
<L>Her whole Conver&s;e <HI>Humility</HI> be&s;pake.</L>
<L>So <HI>graceful</HI> was her <HI>Ge&s;ture</HI>, it did move,</L>
<L>At once, Beholders to <HI>admire</HI> and <HI>love</HI>.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>The&s;e were <HI>Saul</HI>'s Daughters. And by the&s;e the Ki$</L>
<L>Ruin on <HI>David</HI> did de&s;ign to bring.</L>
<L><PB N="25" REF="38">$y one of the&s;e he hoped to prevail:</L>
<L>$word$ all his other <HI>Stratagems</HI> &s;hould fail.</L>
<L>$ne of the&s;e Ladies promi&s;ed had been</L>
<L>$o who&s;oe'er &s;hould kill the <HI>Phili&s;tin</HI>.</L>
<L>Which <HI>David</HI> having done might ju&s;tly claim</L>
<L>$ne; but the King had Power which, to name.</L>
<L>$e therefore <HI>Merab</HI> fir&s;t a&s;&s;ign'd to be</L>
