<HEAD>CHAPTER I.</HEAD>
<LG>
<L>NOW travels <HI>David</HI> with a thoughtful Mind,<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 <HI>Sam.</HI> 21.</NOTE></L>
<L>Uncertain where a &s;afe <HI>Retreat</HI> to find:</L>
<L>$or though, while pro&s;p'rous his Affairs did &s;tand,</L>
<L>$e Friends, and Servants <HI>many</HI>, could command;</L>
<L>$et now, that Frowns had wrink'led Fortune's Face,</L>
<L>$e knew not where to find a re&s;ting Place.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>In this perplexed State, his pious Mind</L>
<L>$as, to Con&s;ult the <HI>Oracle</HI>, inclin'd;</L>
<L>$he <HI>inambiguous</HI> Oracle, from whence</L>
<L><HI>$hovah</HI> &s;ecret Coun&s;els did di&s;pen&s;e:</L>
<L><PB N="64" REF="78">And <HI>undeceiving</HI> An&s;wers always gave</L>
<L>To &s;uch as, with an hone&s;t Mind, did crave.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>To <HI>Nob</HI> his weary Steps he therefore bends&punc;</L>
<L><HI>(Nob</HI> was a City of the Prie&s;ts, his Friends)</L>
<L>And to <HI>Ahimelech</HI> he doth repair,</L>
<L>Who then po&s;&s;e&s;s'd the <HI>Pontificial</HI> Chair.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>The rev'rend <HI>Pontiff</HI>, who had nothing heard</L>
<L>Of <HI>David</HI>'s Troubles, now was &s;ore a-feard</L>
<L>To &s;ee him come alone; who, not long &s;ince,</L>
<L>Was royally Attended, like a Prince.</L>
<L>He &s;tartled at the Sight: nor could forbear</L>
<L>To ask, Why <HI>unattended</HI> he came there.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>It hap'ned, that a certain <HI>Edomite</HI>,</L>
<L>Who to the <HI>Hebrews</HI> was a <HI>Pro&s;elyte</HI>,</L>
<L>(One who had Charge and Over&s;ight of all</L>
<L>The <HI>Herds</HI>, and <HI>Herd-men</HI>, that belong'd to <HI>S$</HI></L>
<L>Was pre&s;ent there; whether detain'd by Vow</L>
<L>Or on what other Score, I know not how.</L>
<L><PB N="65" REF="79">$im, &s;tanding in a Corner, <HI>David</HI> &s;py'd,</L>
<L>$efore he to <HI>Ahimelech</HI> reply'd;</L>
<L>$nd, knowing well the Man, he was afraid</L>
<L>$is Friend, the Prie&s;t, would be by him betray'd,</L>
<L>$word$ after he the King's Di&s;plea&s;ure knew,</L>
<L>$e any Kindne&s;s unto him &s;hould &s;hew.</L>
<L>$e&s;t therefore <HI>into Danger</HI> he &s;hould bring</L>
<L>$is Friend, or <HI>out of Favour</HI> with the King;</L>
<L>$e held it be&s;t his Troubles to conceal,</L>
<L>$nd not his adver&s;e Fortune to reveal:</L>
<L>$hat, if this <HI>Pick-thank</HI> &s;hould relate to <HI>Saul</HI></L>
<L>$ght that, again&s;t the <HI>Prie&s;t</HI>, &s;hould &s;tir his Gall;</L>
<L>$he <HI>Prie&s;t</HI> the Accu&s;ation might &s;urmount,</L>
<L>$nd place his Kindne&s;s to the <HI>King</HI>'s Account.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>He therefore gave the <HI>Prie&s;t</HI> to under&s;tand,</L>
<L>$is coming thus, was by the <HI>King</HI>'s Command:</L>
<L>$ho, he pretended, had di&s;patch'd him &s;o,</L>
<L>$at none his &s;ecret Enterprize might know;</L>
<L>$d that his Servants he before did &s;end</L>
<L>$word$ &s;uch a Place, his coming to attend.</L>
<L><PB N="66" REF="80">Adding, that in &s;uch ha&s;t he came away</L>
<L>(The Kings Command admitting no delay)</L>
<L>That of Provi&s;ion he had never thought;</L>
<L>Nor had his Sword, or Weapons with him brou$</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>The guiltle&s;s <HI>Prie&s;t</HI>, with un&s;u&s;pecting Ear,</L>
<L>This feigned Story, for a Truth, did hear.</L>
<L>And, not with <HI>Victuals</HI> only him &s;upply'd,</L>
<L>But arm'd him with <HI>Goliah's Sword</HI> be&s;ide:</L>
<L>Which, offer'd to the Lord, when he was &s;lai$</L>
<L>Did with the <HI>Prie&s;t</HI> unto that time remain.</L>
<L>Nay, wanting other, he the <HI>Shew-Bread</HI> gave</L>
<L>Appointed for the <HI>Prie&s;ts</HI> alone to have,</L>
<L>In doing which, he Errs that thinks he Err'd</L>
<L>Since <HI>Mercy is to Sacrifice preferr'd</HI>.</L>
<L>Yet e're he gave the con&s;ecrated Bread,</L>
<L>He ask'd, if They, who &s;hould therewith be</L>
<L>Were Clean. <HI>Who will of Holy Things partake</HI>,</L>
<L><HI>Mu&s;t what&s;oever makes Unclean for&s;ake.</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Thus furni&s;h'd, <HI>David</HI> did from <HI>Nob</HI> depar$</L>
<L>And &s;et his Face for <HI>Gath</HI>, with heavy Hea$</L>
<L><PB N="67" REF="81">Not knowing el&s;e, where he his Head might hide:</L>
<L>Nor could he long in Safety there abide.</L>
<L>The Servants of King <HI>Achi&s;h</HI> quickly knew</L>
<L>That he was <HI>David</HI> who <HI>Goliah</HI> &s;lew.</L>
<L>$nd &s;trait recounted (to incen&s;e their King)</L>
<L>What e'r&s;t the <HI>Hebrew</HI> Dames of him did &s;ing,</L>
<L>When, in their Dancing and Triumphant Strain,</L>
<L>They brag'd, That he had his <HI>Ten Thou&s;ands &s;lain</HI>.</L>
<L>This <HI>David</HI> heard: but would not &s;eem to hear,</L>
<L>$oncealing, with his utmo&s;t Care, his Fear;</L>
<L>$ill, by a <HI>Stratagem</HI>, he found a way</L>
<L>$im&s;elf, from <HI>Gath</HI>, in Safety to convey.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Got, pa&s;t the Confines of King <HI>Achi&s;h</HI> Land,</L>
<L>$word$ <HI>I&s;ra'el</HI>'s Coa&s;t again; He's at a &s;tand</L>
<L>$hich way to take, or whither to direct</L>
<L>$is wandring Feet: where he might, un&s;u&s;pect,</L>
<L>$&s;conded lie, until tho&s;e Clouds were pa&s;t,</L>
<L>$ith which his <HI>Hemi&s;phear</HI> was overca&s;t.</L>
<L>$word$ in the World he did not know a Friend,</L>
<L>$hom he could tru&s;t: and who could him defend.</L>
<L><PB N="68" REF="82">And <HI>Saul</HI>, if once di&s;cov'red, would (he knew)</L>
<L>Through all the Tribes of <HI>I&s;ra'el</HI> him pur&s;ue.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>No long time had he to deliberate</L>
<L>What Cour&s;e to take, &s;o <HI>pre&s;&s;ing</HI> was his Fate:</L>
<L>Yet, in tho&s;e Moments, many a Place was broug$</L>
<L>Under the Judgment of his winged Thought.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><NOTE PLACE="marg">1 <HI>Sam.</HI> 22.</NOTE>Of all the <HI>Refuges</HI> his wary Mind</L>
<L>Could, in &s;uch ha&s;te, and on a &s;uddain, find,</L>
<L>None pleas'd him better, than a certain <HI>Cave</HI>,</L>
<L>To which its Name the Town <HI>Adullam</HI> gave.</L>
<L>A &s;pacious Cave it was; yet known to few:</L>
<L>Remote from <HI>Gibeah</HI>, and from publick View</L>
<L>And (which did recommend it to his State)</L>
<L>'Twas in the Tribe of <HI>Judah</HI> &s;ituate;</L>
<L><HI>Judah</HI>, the Tribe from which he &s;prang, and wh$</L>
<L>He had mo&s;t Rea&s;on to expect Defence.</L>
<L>This Solitary Cave, he thought, was be&s;t.</L>
<L>Where, for a while, he hop'd to find &s;ome R$</L>
<L>The Towns and Cities therefore he for&s;ook,</L>
<L>And to <HI>Adullam</HI>'s Cave him&s;elf betook.</L>
<L><PB N="69" REF="83">Where long he had not been, before he &s;py'd</L>
<L>$word$ Friend pa&s;s by, who&s;e Faith he oft had try'd:</L>
<L>$y whom, unto his Brethren, and his Friends,</L>
<L>He notice of his &s;afe Arrival &s;ends.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>With Joy, like that which <HI>Jacob</HI> did revive,</L>
<L>When news was brought that <HI>Jo&s;eph</HI> was alive,</L>
<L>Did good old <HI>Je&s;&s;e</HI> the good Tydings hear</L>
<L>$hat <HI>David</HI> was in Safety, and &s;o near:</L>
<L>And forthwith he, his Wife, and ev'ry Son,</L>
<L>With all their Families, to <HI>David</HI> run,</L>
<L>$im to Embrace, and cheer him in his Straight&punc;</L>
<L>Re&s;olv'd henceforth to run a common Fate.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>The <HI>Bruit</HI> hereof &s;oon &s;pread, and that <HI>Report</HI></L>
<L>$ade others al&s;o unto him re&s;ort.</L>
<L>$hoe'er was in <HI>Di&s;tre&s;s</HI>, or <HI>Di&s;content</HI>;</L>
